<div class="modal small show" id="glass-types-info-modal" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-hidden="true">
    <div class="modal-header">
        <h3>Glass Type Definitions</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="modal-body modal-content-scroll">
        <dl>
            <dt>Clear Single Pane</dt>
            <dd>No coatings on glass.</dd>

            <dt>Tinted Single Pane</dt>
            <dd>No coatings on glass.</dd>

            <dt>Clear Double Pane (IG)</dt>
            <dd>Two panes of clear glass w/ no coatings separated by an air gap.</dd>

            <dt>Tinted Double Pane (IG)</dt>
            <dd>Two panes separated by an air gap.  Coating typically on surface 1 or 2.</dd>

            <dt>Low E Type I</dt>
            <dd>Pyrolytic or hardcoat low E.  Some examples of this type of low E glass are: Pilkington Energy Advantage, PPG Sungate 500, and AGC Planibel G.   In The Glass Checklist, low E coating is assumed to be on Surface 2 for film applied on interior films and on Surface 3 for exterior films.</dd>

            <dt>Low E Type II</dt>
            <dd>Single Silver sputtered softcoat low E.  Some examples of this type of low E glass are: Cardinal Glass Low E - 178, AGC Planibel Top NT, PPG Sungate 100, SGG Planitherm T and Pilkington Optitherm SN.  In The Glass Checklist, low E coating is assumed to be on Surface 2 for film applied on interior films and on Surface 3 for exterior films.</dd>

            <dt>Low E Type III</dt>
            <dd>Double Silver sputtered softcoat low E.  Some examples of this type of low E glass are: Cardinal Glass Low E2  - 272, PPG Solarban 60, AGC Planibel NT, Pilkington Suncool HPand SGG Cool-Lite SKN.  In The Glass Checklist, low E coating is assumed to be on Surface 2 for film applied on interior films and on Surface 3 for exterior films.</dd>
        </dl>
    </div>
    <div class="modal-footer">
        <button class="btn" data-dismiss="modal" aria-hidden="true">Ok</button>
    </div>
</div>